[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1199},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F13\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F13\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F13\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F13\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start\u002F":1182,"related:\u002Fen\u002Freact\u002F2022\u002F10\u002F13\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start\u002F":1191},"\u002Freact\u002F20221013\u002F1993947189\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1160,"date":1161,"description":1162,"extension":1163,"lang":1164,"meta":1165,"navigation":123,"path":1166,"readingMinutes":1167,"seo":1168,"standalone":1169,"stem":1170,"tags":1171,"tldr":1178,"updated":1179,"url":1180,"__hash__":1181},"content\u002Fen\u002FReact\u002Flearn-react-29-react-redux-quick-start.md","Learn React Eventually, So Why Not Now? - React Redux: Redux and a Quick Start - (29)","1003048818",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1151},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,30,36,39,47,241,252,267,271,274,278,281,292,320,323,346,349,353,362,383,421,443,517,520,524,539,548,563,582,614,626,667,676,738,748,775,790,799,847,865,874,881,890,898,907,928,977,996,1096,1099,1123,1131,1135,1138,1147],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"This post kicks off a brand new chapter. I'm only splitting it into two parts though, so there's a bit less to cover than usual. So what exactly is Redux? Let's get to know it in this post.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"what-is-redux","What is Redux?",[17,25,26],{},"So what is Redux? Redux is basically a state management tool. You can also think of it as a container — it helps us manage the state of an entire web app, and Redux itself can be used on its own.",[17,28,29],{},"Like I just said, Redux is a tool built specifically for state management and it can run standalone. That's why right on the official homepage you'll see this line:",[31,32,33],"blockquote",{},[17,34,35],{},"A Predictable State Container for JS Apps",[17,37,38],{},"So we know Redux can be used independently. But some people see Redux and assume it's React's own state management tool, kind of like Vuex is for Vue. Because Redux can run on its own, though, you can actually use it with frameworks and libraries other than React too — Angular, Vue, jQuery, and so on. On top of that, Redux is tiny, only about 2kb.",[17,40,41,42,46],{},"At this point you might be thinking back to the ",[43,44,45],"code",{},"useReducer"," example from an earlier chapter:",[48,49,54],"pre",{"className":50,"code":51,"language":52,"meta":53,"style":53},"language-jsx shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","const reducer = (state, action) => {\n  switch(action.type) {\n    case 'increment':\n      return { count: state.count + 1 };\n    case 'decrement':\n      return { count: state.count - 1 };\n    default:\n      return { count: 0 }\n  }\n}\n\nconst App = () => {\n  const initialState = {\n    count: 0,\n  };\n\n  const [state, dispatch] = React.useReducer(reducer, initialState);\n\n  return (\n    \u003Cdiv>\n      Count: {state.count}\n      \u003Cbr \u002F>\n      \u003Cbutton onClick={() => dispatch({ type: \"decrement\" })}>Decrement\u003C\u002Fbutton>\n      \u003Cbutton onClick={() => dispatch({ type: \"increment\" })}>Increment\u003C\u002Fbutton>\n    \u003C\u002Fdiv>\n  );\n}\n\nconst app = document.querySelector('#app');\nconst root = ReactDOM.createRoot(app);\nroot.render(\u003CApp \u002F>);\n","jsx","",[43,55,56,64,70,76,82,88,94,100,106,112,118,125,131,137,143,149,154,160,165,171,177,183,189,195,201,207,213,218,223,229,235],{"__ignoreMap":53},[57,58,61],"span",{"class":59,"line":60},"line",1,[57,62,63],{},"const reducer = (state, action) => {\n",[57,65,67],{"class":59,"line":66},2,[57,68,69],{},"  switch(action.type) {\n",[57,71,